INSERT INTO `node_revisions` VALUES(25, 144, 3, 'Case Study: Placeography', 'I am a web designer at Minnesota Historical Society and the Society has put together a web site called Placeography.org. Launched just recently in February 2008 it is a form based semantic wiki running on Mediawiki software collecting the history and memory of places. \r\n\r\nIn addition to being a web designer I was also a community and neighborhood organizer in St. Paul and have applied knowledge of communities with my web experience in building Placeography. \r\n\r\nIn order to succeed in its task of gathering history, it is being developed as a community tool aiding neighborhood, educational, history and preservation organizations in networking, development and preservation. The incorporation of community into the wiki through portal pages makes the wiki both relevant and successful. \r\n\r\n<h3>Creation of Portals </h3>\r\n\r\nOn Placeography portals are tied to a particular organization such as a local historical society, neighborhood organization, college, preservation group, or other organization. Such organizations that have an interest in creating and updating a number of articles pertaining to their geographical or subject base may have a portal created. \r\n\r\nI would like to present the process in which we developed the site as well as the ideas that shaped the community building strategies behind it. If you are interested and would like me to present I would love to hear from you and discuss it more. ', 'I am a web designer at Minnesota Historical Society and the Society has put together a web site called Placeography.org. Launched just recently in February 2008 it is a form based semantic wiki running on Mediawiki software collecting the history and memory of places. \r\n\r\nIn addition to being a web designer I was also a community and neighborhood organizer in St. Paul and have applied knowledge of communities with my web experience in building Placeography. \r\n\r', '', 1215709183, 1);
INSERT INTO `node_revisions` VALUES(24, 145, 3, 'Joe Hoover', 'Joe Hoover is a web designer/developer for the Minnesota Historical Society working on (among other things) their social web presence.\r\n\r\nIn his past life, Hoover was a community organizer for different Saint Paul neighborhoods as well as a nationally syndicated political cartoonist on Gay, Lesbian, Bisexual and Transgender issues.\r\n\r\nHoover now lives in Richfield, Minnesota, doing community building experiments on unsuspecting suburban locals and neighbors.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.joehoover.org\r\nhttp://www.76street.org', 'Joe Hoover is a web designer/developer for the Minnesota Historical Society working on (among other things) their social web presence.\r\n\r\nIn his past life, Hoover was a community organizer for different Saint Paul neighborhoods as well as a nationally syndicated political cartoonist on Gay, Lesbian, Bisexual and Transgender issues.\r\n\r\nHoover now lives in Richfield, Minnesota, doing community building experiments on unsuspecting suburban locals and neighbors.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.joehoover.org\r\nhttp://www.76street.org', '', 1215727758, 1);
INSERT INTO `node_revisions` VALUES(25, 146, 3, 'Semantic Mediawiki and the Human Element', 'Placeography.org was launched by the Minnesota Historical Society in February of this year it''s mission was simple, to gather the history of places and to collect memories from those who experienced those places.\r\n\r\nTo achieve that goal MHS uses a semantic based MediaWiki. However, the key to its success would be not only in it''s technology but also how well a community could be created around it.\r\n\r\nUsing a direct and personal approach to individuals and organizations who have become stakeholders and contributing partners, the Minnesota Historical Society has facilitated the organization of the vibrant Placeography community.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.placeography.org\r\nhttp://www.mnhs.org', 'Placeography.org was launched by the Minnesota Historical Society in February of this year it''s mission was simple, to gather the history of places and to collect memories from those who experienced those places.\r\n\r\nTo achieve that goal MHS uses a semantic based MediaWiki. However, the key to its success would be not only in it''s technology but also how well a community could be created around it.\r\n\r', '', 1215727865, 1);
INSERT INTO `node_revisions` VALUES(27, 147, 3, 'Malik Bush', 'Malik, President and Founder of IdeaCorps Training and Consulting Inc. as well as its IdeaCorps Data Services Division brings with him over 21 years of management, development, and training experience in corporate, educational and non-profit settings. As a trained and experienced educator who is also an entrepreneur he is concerned not only with how material is presented, but also whether people can perform the task in question.  Malik’s skill as a speaker and inspirational force is always focused on creating business value by delivering training that solves real and measurable business problems.', 'Malik, President and Founder of IdeaCorps Training and Consulting Inc. as well as its IdeaCorps Data Services Division brings with him over 21 years of management, development, and training experience in corporate, educational and non-profit settings. As a trained and experienced educator who is also an entrepreneur he is concerned not only with how material is presented, but also whether people can perform the task in question.', '', 1215728103, 1);
INSERT INTO `node_revisions` VALUES(28, 148, 3, 'Drupal Basics - Made Super Extra Special Easy', 'Course Description: Come along for a fun and engaging jaunt that will give you the courage to get started building your first Drupal site.  Not only is it not as hard as you thought but it is positively down right easy and so remarkably rewarding to take the work of others and slap your name on it to make you look brilliant.  By the end of today''s session you will have an idea why everyone is making such a big darn deal about the Drupal stuff and you will have a link to download a template you can use to start your first site.  We will assume that you know nothing about Drupal or even website development.  The learner who would best benefit from the class is one who just figured out that they need a website and have heard about Drupal and want to see if this thing that the Geeks are so excited about is worth your time and energy.\r\n\r\nInstructor Assumptions: We will assume that the learner has the intention to use a hosted Drupal solution that minimizes the amount that we will need to know about server issues.  This course will focus on use of Drupal 5.x.\r\n\r\nCourse Outline*:\r\n\r\n   1. Drupal - Why should you care\r\n   2. Peruse a few example sites and get inspired, impressed or even a little intimidated\r\n   3. Consider the easiest route into your own site - a simple theme that someone else built\r\n   4. Pick-A-Theme Party\r\n   5. Explore the Aspects and ways to control a Theme\r\n   6. Fill in some important peices of information\r\n   7. Go Home and brag to your friends about your supreme geekishness (make sure you choose carefully who you choose to brag to - not everyone will understand what a big deal this is - don''t bother explaining...It''s a Drupal thing they wouldn''t understand)\r\n\r\n    * *Course outline subject to change upon instructor, whim, fancy and time availability', 'Course Description: Come along for a fun and engaging jaunt that will give you the courage to get started building your first Drupal site.  Not only is it not as hard as you thought but it is positively down right easy and so remarkably rewarding to take the work of others and slap your name on it to make you look brilliant.  By the end of today''s session you will have an idea why everyone is making such a big darn deal about the Drupal stuff and you will have a link to download a template you can use to start your first site.', '', 1215728205, 1);
